                    breaks in the print edition and should thus be marked with <att xml:lang="en">ed</att>="shamela"</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">It remains unclear to which extent publication dates for individual issues are correct. The transcribers seemingly
                    normalised <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">hijrī</foreign> dates for the first two years (1906-1907) and then
                    recorded all issue as having been published on the first of each Gregorian month. This needs to be checked against the
                    image files and other sources.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Some phenomena have been marked in red spans by <ref target="http://shamela.ws/index.php/book/26523" xml:lang="en">
                  <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">al-maktabat al-shāmila</foreign>
               </ref>. Red spans that contained three points only were
                    considered indicators of ellipses and transformed into <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi> with <att xml:lang="en">resp</att>="#org_MS". Upon further
                    scrutiny, it turned out that most, if not all, of these <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi>s indicated the division between two halfs of the
                    line of a <foreign xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-ijmes">qaṣīda</foreign>. I have converted all <gi xml:lang="en">p</gi>s that contained two
                    short lines of text divided by <gi xml:lang="en">gap</gi> into <gi xml:lang="en">lg</gi> of <att xml:lang="en">type</att>="bayt" with <gi xml:lang="en">l</gi> child elements.
                    All other red spans have been retained as <gi xml:lang="en">hi</gi>.</p>
            </editorialDecl>
